# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeenshire
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] The election used the 10 wards created by the Formation Electoral Arrangements in 1974.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Each ward elected one councillor using first-past-the-post voting.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Banff and Buchan was a non-partisan district.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Only a few members of political parties contested the election and all but three of the 18 seats were won by independents.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Prior to 1974, the area that was to become Banff and Buchan, was split between two counties – the County of Banff and the County of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Within that were five of the 11 burghs of the County of Banff (Aberchirder, Banff, Fraserburgh, Macduff and Portsoy) and two of the 10 burghs of the County of Aberdeen (Peterhead, Rosehearty and Turriff).
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] These were all small burghs so the burgh council had limited powers which included some control over planning as well as local taxation, building control, housing, lighting and drainage with the rest of the local government responsibility falling to the county council.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] The Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973 implemented most of the recommendations in the Wheatly Report.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] The northeastern part of the County of Baff which included the five burghs was combined with the northern part of the County of Abrdeen and was placed into the Banff and Buchan district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Banff and Buchan, like the other three districts in Grampian excluding the City of Aberdeen, was non-partisan and controlled by Independent candidates who won all 15 of the 18 seats.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] The Conservatives controlled the regional council which held its first election on the same day.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Across Scotland, Labour won the most votes, the most seats and the most councils of any party.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-gordon-district-council-election] The election used the 12 wards created by the Formation Electoral Arrangements in 1974.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-gordon-district-council-election] The council was left in no overall control following the election.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-gordon-district-council-election] Independent candidates won six of the 12 seats.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-gordon-district-council-election] The Conservatives were the largest party after they took four seats while the Liberals won two seats.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-gordon-district-council-election] Prior to 1974, the area that was to become Gordon, contained were five of the 10 burghs of the County of Aberdeen (Ellon, Huntly, Inverurie, Kintore and Oldmeldrum).
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-gordon-district-council-election] The central part of the County of Aberdeen which included the five burghs was placed into the Gordon district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-gordon-district-council-election] Gordon was left in no overall control following the election but, like the three of the other districts in Grampian except the City of Aberdeen, saw more independent candidates elected than political parties.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-gordon-district-council-election] Independents took six seats, the Conservatives won four seats and the Liberals won the remaining two seats.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Kincardine and Deeside was a non-partisan district.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Only a few political party members contested the election and all but two of the 12 seats were won by independents.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] The remaining two seats were won by the Conservatives.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Prior to 1974, the area that was to become Kincardine and Deeside, was split between two counties – the County of Aberdeen and the County of Kincardine.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Within that were one of the 10 burghs of the County of Aberdeen (Ballater) and all four of the burghs of the County of Kincardine (Banchory, Inverbervie, Laurencekirk and Stonehaven).
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] The County of Kincardine which included the four burghs was combined with the southern area including Ballater from the County of Aberdeen and was placed into the Kincardine and Deeside district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeenshire/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Kincardine and Deeside, like three of the other districts in Grampian except the City of Aberdeen, was non-partisan and controlled by independent candidates who won all but two of the 12 seats.
[src:aberdeenshire/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The **fourth election to Grampian Regional Council** was held on 8 May 1986 as part of the wider 1986 Scottish regional elections.
[src:aberdeenshire/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The election saw the Conservatives suffering heavy losses, which were in turn picked up by the various other parties.
[src:aberdeenshire/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The Labour Party emerged as the single largest force on the 57 seat council, although all parties fell well short of the 29 seats needed for a majority.
[src:aberdeenshire/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The election was particularly devastating for the Conservatives in the region given that they had controlled the council since its creation in 1974.
[src:aberdeenshire/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] Following the election control of the council was undertaken by a minority administration composed of Independent, SNP, and SDP-Liberal Alliance councillors.
[src:aberdeenshire/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The councils new convenor was the Independent councillor Geoffrey Hadley.
[src:aberdeenshire/1990-grampian-regional-council-election] The **1990 Grampian Regional Council election**, the fifth election to Grampian Regional Council, was held on 3 May 1990 as part of the wider 1990 Scottish regional elections.
[src:aberdeenshire/1990-grampian-regional-council-election] The election saw Labour take the most seats, with the Conservatives falling sharply to finish fourth in terms of councillors.
[src:aberdeenshire/1994-grampian-regional-council-election] The **1994 Grampian Regional Council election**, the sixth and final election to Grampian Regional Council, was held on 5 May 1994 as part of the wider 1994 Scottish regional elections.
[src:aberdeenshire/1994-grampian-regional-council-election] The election saw the Liberal Democrats take the most seats, although the Scottish National Party had a higher number of votes.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] It takes its name from the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which had substantially different boundaries.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The Aberdeenshire Council area includes all of the areas of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire except the area making up Aberdeen City Council area, as well as part of Banffshire.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The historic county boundaries are still officially used for a few purposes, namely land registration and lieutenancy.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire Council is headquartered at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, making it the only Scottish council whose headquarters are located outside its jurisdiction.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeen itself forms a different council area (Aberdeen City).
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire borders onto Angus and Perth and Kinross to the south, Highland and Moray to the west and Aberdeen City to the east.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Traditionally, it has depended economically on the primary sector (agriculture, fishing, and forestry) and related processing industries.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Over the last 40 years, the development of the oil and gas industry and associated service sector has broadened Aberdeenshire's economic base, and contributed to a rapid population growth of some 50% since 1975.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Its land represents 8% of Scotland's overall territory.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] It covers an area of 6,313 square kilometres (2,437 sq mi).
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a rich prehistoric and historical heritage.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] It is the locus of a large number of Neolithic and Bronze Age archaeological sites, including Longman Hill, Kempstone Hill, Catto Long Barrow and Cairn Lee.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The area was settled in the Bronze Age by the Beaker culture, who arrived from the south around 2000–1800 BC.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Stone circles and cairns were constructed predominantly in this era.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Around the 1st century AD, the Taexali people, who left little history, were believed to have resided along the coast.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The Picts were the next documented inhabitants of the area and were no later than 800–900 AD.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The Romans also were in the area during this period, as they left signs at Kintore.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Christianity influenced the inhabitants early on, and there were Celtic monasteries at Old Deer and Monymusk.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Since medieval times, there have been many traditional paths that crossed the Mounth (a spur of mountainous land that extends from the higher inland range to the North Sea slightly north of Stonehaven) through present-day Aberdeenshire from the Scottish Lowlands to the Highlands.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Some of the most well known and historically important trackways are the Causey Mounth and Elsick Mounth.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire played an important role in the fighting between the Scottish dynasties.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] During the Anglo-Norman penetration, other families arrive, such as House of Balliol, Clan Bruce, and Clan Cumming (Comyn).
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] During the Scottish Wars of Independence, the King of England Edward I travelled across the area twice with his invading army, in 1296 and 1303.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] In 1307, Robert the Bruce was victorious near Inverurie.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] These new families set the stage for the upcoming rivalries during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] This rivalry grew worse during and after the Protestant Reformation when religion was another reason for conflict between the clans.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The Gordon family adhered to Catholicism and the Forbeses to Protestantism.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire was the historic seat of the clan Dempster.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Three universities were founded in the area prior to the 17th century, King's College in Old Aberdeen (1494), Marischal College in Aberdeen (1593), and the University of Fraserburgh (1592).
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] During the 17th century, Aberdeenshire was the location of more fighting, centred on the Marquess of Montrose and the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] This period also saw increased wealth due to the increase in trade with Germany, Poland, and the Low Countries.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] After the end of the Revolution of 1688, an extended peaceful period was interrupted only by fleeting events such as the Rising of 1715 and the Rising of 1745.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The latter resulted in the end of the ascendancy of Episcopalianism and the feudal power of landowners.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] An era began of increased agricultural and industrial progress.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The present council area is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which has different boundaries and ceased to be used for local government purposes in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Local government functions were shared between the two levels.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The modern council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] It covers the combined area of the Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside districts that had been created in 1975.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The present Aberdeenshire Council area therefore consists of all of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire (except the area of those two counties making up Aberdeen City), as well as the north-east portions of Banffshire.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The population of the council area has risen over 50% since 1971 to approximately 265,080 in 2024, representing 4.7% of Scotland's total.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's population has increased by 9.1% since 2001, while Scotland's total population grew by 3.8%.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The census lists a relatively high proportion of under 16s and slightly fewer working-age people compared with the Scottish average.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is one of the most homogeneous/indigenous regions of the UK.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] In 2011, 82.2% of residents identified as 'White Scottish', followed by 12.3% who are 'White British', whilst ethnic minorities constitute only 0.9% of the population.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The largest ethnic minority group is Asian Scottish/British at 0.8%.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] In addition to the English language, 48.8% of residents reported being able to speak and understand the Scots language.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,382 residents aged three and over, 121,797 (47.5%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] This is the greatest proportion of Scots speakers of any Scottish council area.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,377 residents aged three and over, 3,579 (1.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is estimated at £3,496M (2011), representing 5.2% of the Scottish total.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy is closely linked to Aberdeen City's (GDP £7,906M), and in 2011, the region as a whole was calculated to contribute 16.8% of Scotland's GDP.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Between 2012 and 2014, the combined Aberdeenshire and Aberdeen City economic forecast GDP growth rate is 8.6%, the highest growth rate of any local council area in the UK and above the Scottish rate of 4.8%.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] A significant proportion of Aberdeenshire's working residents commute to Aberdeen City for work, varying from 11.5% from Fraserburgh to 65% from Westhill.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Average Gross Weekly Earnings (for full-time employees employed in workplaces in Aberdeenshire in 2011) are £572.60.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the Scottish average by £2.10 and a fall of 2.6% on the 2010 figure.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The average gross weekly pay of people resident in Aberdeenshire is much higher, at £741.90, as many people commute out of Aberdeenshire, principally into Aberdeen City.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Total employment (excluding farm data) in Aberdeenshire is estimated at 93,700 employees (Business Register and Employment Survey 2009).
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The majority of employees work within the service sector, predominantly in public administration, education and health.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Almost 19% of employment is within the public sector.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy remains closely linked to Aberdeen City's and the North Sea oil industry, with many employees in oil-related jobs.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] The average monthly unemployment (claimant count) rate for Aberdeenshire in 2011 was 1.5%.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the average rate of Aberdeen City (2.3%), Scotland (4.2%) and the UK (3.8%).
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] In the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'No' by a percentage of 60.4%.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] In the 2016 European Union membership referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'Remain' by the third lowest margin of 55.0%.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] First and second lowest margin for 'Remain' were Moray (50.1%) and Dumfries and Galloway (53.1%).
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] There are numerous rivers and burns in Aberdeenshire, including Cowie Water, Carron Water, Burn of Muchalls, River Dee, River Don, River Ury, River Ythan, Water of Feugh, Burn of Myrehouse, Laeca Burn and Luther Water.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Numerous bays and estuaries are found along the seacoast of Aberdeenshire, including Banff Bay, Ythan Estuary, Stonehaven Bay and Thornyhive Bay.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a marine west coast climate on the Köppen climate classification.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is in the rain shadow of the Grampians, therefore it has a generally dry climate for a maritime region, with portions of the coast receiving 25 inches (64 cm) of moisture annually.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Summers are mild, and winters are typically cold in Aberdeenshire; Coastal temperatures are moderated by the North Sea such that coastal areas are typically cooler in the summer and warmer in the winter than inland locations.
[src:aberdeenshire/aberdeenshire] Coastal areas are also subject to haar, or coastal fog.
